all in all just a perfect game. 10/10 no complaints.
and the of course the ending is extremely well done i dont really have anything to say about it
and seeing the way that he doesn't actually just exist in a puzzle solving vacuum and how he actually lives in the world is just so so good

unwound future is also the first time we get a look into hershel's backstory and i really do have to say after not really getting any of that the first two games playing through it for the first time is very very cool
and finally, the plot is a perfect blend of intense character impact that azran legacy tries to do mixed with trippy world-altering impact that is present in the first two games
the cast of characters is memorable, with future luke (clive) and dimitri being great one-offs, and of course don paolo getting one of the most satisfying redemption arcs ive ever seen

there's technically only one locale for the whole game, london, but the world is detailed and expansive and it always feels like there's something interesting to look at when you're exploring a new area

the puzzles are at just an appropriate amount of difficulty and there's a good variety of them - in the first two games they were sometimes a little unfair whereas starting in the 3ds era the puzzles started to feel a bit too easy

finally, #1! the third game, unwound future

i'm pretty sure it's generally agreed upon in the layton community that this is the best game in the series and i agree. it strikes a perfect balance between the charm of the older games and the polish and complexity of the newer games https://t.co/57JPbRqnWY
thats it i aint got nothin else. people talk about how good unwound future is, and they're right, but diabolical box is HIGHLY underrated
and also iris is probably my favourite credits theme and tbh one of my favourite songs composed for a video game ever

the only complaint i have about it is that, and ive said this before, but flora reeeeeally got screwed over in this game and i do feel bad about that. but i can ignore that because the rest of it is just so good

but really the main thing that diabolical box does well is its story. the backstory of anton and sophia is SO cute and touching and ends on a perfect bittersweet note that is signature to the layton franchise
also this game made layton face to the side instead of facing front which thank GOD for that

honestly i don't really have too much to say about this one other than it changed what wasn't good about curious village and improved what was good about it. dynamic locales, a slight improvement in puzzle quality, better character work, etc

that brings us to #2! the second game, diabolical box

i feel similarly about this game as i do last specter in that it's literally just curious village but better. except, diabolical box's plot is a million times more compelling https://t.co/HmJCT37AHQ
and that plus the very cool upheaval of the formula makes me feel comfortable putting it in third

i think unwound future has the better WRITTEN ending but there's something about how the climax of the story is presented in azran legacy that just hits me really hard, idk

i agree there are problems with it but i can't ignore the effect it has on me yknow

like i was talking about earlier i still haven't managed to play the ending of azran legacy without crying and it's just a combination of the character interactions, the broader messages, the music, and a bunch of other things

that being said, the ending of the game is still very beautiful at face value if you just take it for what it is, and i also want to highlight the incredible work that the OST does at the ed of azran legacy to supplement its impact
they were going for a lot of deep, character-driven impact at the end of the game and i don't really know if they built any of it up enough to feel like the twists made sense basically

there were a LOT of very big plot twists at the end of the game and i won't spoil them but i'll say this:

layton and descole? believable. sure. that one was done relatively well.
bronev's backstory? a little out of left field.
emmy's twist? def could have been done better

now let's talk about PLOT. azran legacy is obviously extremely plot heavy, and again i feel like either you love it or you hate it

i think that it succeeded in making a climactic and satisfying ending to the azran arc, but not without flaws

and honestly i love a good few of the one off characters we get to meet along the way

also aurora and sycamore are wonderful (well, sycamore before he. yknow.)

some people think that the globetrotting takes away from the overall plot (which we will talk about in a moment), but i don't really think it does - i think the section is maybe a bit long but it does a good job at establishing the gravity and significance of the azran

and even though each locale was relatively small they kinda each felt like their own mini curious village one-off which i thought was really really cool

(for the record my favourite town in the game is san grio)

i also think that the interactivity of the world was a big improvement over miracle mask. the scenes were much more dynamic and immersive; objects in a scene tended to react more when you tapped them etc

it really kinda upended the traditional layton format of having a central location and made the world rather expansive

i don't think everyone likes how they did it but i personally found it very cool
i would probably say azran legacy is the game that is the most chock full of content, with the globetrotting section and streetpass functions and all the extra puzzles and minigames
following the general trend of the 3ds games, this one is a polarizing one as well. lots of things to like, a few things that people definitely don't like about it

there are three issues i have with the plot, however:

the first was using descole p much as a plot device. he shows up for like 3 seconds and then dips. i get why it was necessary for him to be there, but after the amount of impact he had in the last game, it felt kinda... weird

personally, i liked that a layton game did a whole everyone-is-happy-and-no-one-died type ending for once. after four games of bittersweetness it was nice to just have an ending where everything turned out for the best. was it a little cheesy? yeah, but i didn't mind that
but anyway aside from the obvious lack of graphical polish i would say that miracle mask's plot is also questionable. again, it's also polarizing
and the dungeon crawling section in the akbadain ruins was very ambitious and very cool. honestly that part is probably what put it over last specter for me

of course a lot of the mechanics got revamped as well, and i for one will forever be grateful to how they changed the investigation system so that im not just tapping aimlessly everywhere for hint coins

miracle mask also really upped the ante with puzzle design - although they'd been slowly working on it from the first game, many of the puzzles starting in the 3ds era felt more interactive and engaging
BUT it was nice to have the familiarity of the whole "small town with a secret" thing in the flashbacks to stansbury

where miracle mask shines for me is in concept and in puzzle design

let's talk concept first: monte d'or is a locale vastly different from any we'd seen in the layton series so far and honestly i found that extremely refreshing

i think MOST people don't like miracle mask because of how the 3d graphics take away from the charm of the original artstyle from the DS games

i see where people are coming from when they say that, but personally it doesn't really get in the way for me that much
tbh i agonized whether to swap this one with last specter bc theyre pretty equal but miracle mask edges it out on mechanics i think

#4 is the fifth game, miracle mask

this game is definitely an either you love it or hate it imo. there are a lot of really cool things in it, but also a lot of criticisms you could make. https://t.co/1ybwoXUVbt

but overall last specter is basically just what you get when you try to make curious village while actually knowing what you're doing. still not flawless - no game is - but you can definitely see the improvements
so like when arianna and tony and everyone else were having this whole Moment with her it didn't really resonate with me and honestly at times i found it kind of cringey

finally, pretty much all of the emotional impact of the story was centered around a non-human creature, loosha, and frankly i didn't find myself getting super attached to her as a character on account of her being... well... a dinosaur
which i dont think is a bad thing, but i think it did make the cinematic reveal of the specter's true identity kind of underwhelming
last specter also marks the beginning of the end of universe-altering plot twists in the way the first three games handled them in favour of the overarching Azran storyline

and some of it is done well! however, the similarities with curious village really come through here imo since when you compare it to diabolical box and unwound future re-centering the plot on the town feels a bit regressive

the MAIN thing that i'd say bogs down last specter is its plot. imo the plot of last specter is very polarizing. it's probably one of the most politically complex storylines in the series, what with all the lines of classism and police corruption
oh! and the episodes. the episodes were a fun addition

on top of that misthallery is just more expansive than st. mystere was, and last specter introduces a bunch of game features like the interactive mystery solving sequences and being able to travel to london

i'd also say the one-off characters like the Bardes and the black ravens are more memorable than the same from curious village. oh and shoutout to last specter for having one of the LEAST likeable characters in the whole series, chief jakes

however, last specter's puzzles and characters are much more engaging than curious village's imo. emmy, descole, and grosky - all extremely strong recurring characters - are introduced in this game, and getting luke's backstory here is also very cute

granted it's easy to see how you could get the two mashed together: they're both the first game in their respective trilogies and both games are centered around one singular locale that have a similar aesthetic (even though in last specter you are able to travel outside the town)

so fun fact: i used to rank last specter below curious village, mostly because curious village had more of a novelty to it for its time and i didn't feel that last specter was distinguishable enough from curious village to stand on its own

after replaying it ive changed my mind

#5 is the fourth game, the last specter

given that this game was basically a series reboot it pretty much just feels like what you'd get if you took curious village and fixed most of the glaring mistakes in it https://t.co/7vz009adjN

anyway the game is definitely a classic! but it is for sure the most flawed out of the six, although that is really not a bad thing. it just shows how well the devs managed to improve on the formula in future games
and i guess to the game's credit that's a consequence of the Big Robot Twist Thing at the end of it but that was definitely a double edged sword even though i respect the boldness of using it

overall the game just suffers from the world being too small and us not getting to spend too much time in it. you come out of the came wanting to have gotten to know most of the characters better - like the whole reinhold family just got thrown out

finally a lot of the puzzles are not especially engaging, with a good number of them being simple math problems or word-based riddles - and a cohesive and charming art style had also not yet been developed for them at this stage either

flora and don paolo are set up well as recurring characters but flora gets STIFFED in the second and third games and while don paolo's arc in game 3 is extremely good he doesn't really have an impact outside of that and gets overshadowed by descole as layton's main rival
the game was fairly short, is the only game to have only one locale to really walk around, and doesn't really introduce many characters that are especially memorable

anyway without further ado: #6 is the first game, curious village

tbh i think that the first game being the weakest is indicative of the quality of the rest of the series and honestly pretty natural. curious village was still trying to figure out the layton formula and it showed https://t.co/7E2ixgH2CE
overall what makes me like any of the games more can be puzzle quality, the way the plot and characters were written, game mechanics, and any other variety of miscellaneous qualities
